<DOC><DOCNO> AP880426-0040 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0232EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Glance     04-26 0274</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea-Glance,0278</SECOND><HEAD>South Korean National Assembly Election At A Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Korea, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here is a brief look at the parties and issues in today'selection:   CANDIDATES: 1,045 for 224 seats in single-member districts.Another 75 seats in the 299-member National Assembly will bedecided according to the parties' nationwide vote proportions.Winners will serve four years.   MAJOR PARTIES: President Roh Tae-woo's Democratic Justice Party;the Reunification Democratic Party of Kim Young-sam; the Party forPeace and Democracy, which split with Reunification to back rivalopposition leader Kim Dae-jung's bid for the presidency in lastDecember's elections; the New Democratic Republican Party of formerPrime Minister Kim Jong-pil.   FORMER ASSEMBLY: Elected in February 1985, it had 276 seats,with the Democratic Justice Party holding 160, the ReunificationDemocratic Party 55, the Party for Peace and Democracy 24, and theNew Democratic Republican Party 8, with the rest held byindependents or splinter groups. Roh won a five-year term in theDecember presidential election with 36 percent of the vote as theopposition vote was mainly split between the two main oppositionparties.   ISSUES: Roh's party says it must win to ensure stability forcontinued progress in the economy and democratic reforms announcedby Roh last summer as the governing party chairman. It accuses theopposition of fomenting unrest. The opposition says a governingparty victory will bring more of the authoritarian rule andcorruption experienced under the administration of former PresidentChun Doo-hwan. Chun's younger brother has been arrested in anembezzlement scandal.   VOTERS: 26.2 million registered. Voting hours were 7 a.m. to 6p.m. at 13,812 polling stations.</TEXT></DOC>